00:03:42.100 --> 00:03:57.520
So I started programming sometime in the third grade, and I really don't like telling that story because it sort of reinforces that, like, oh, no, you have to start programming when you're a little kid or, you know, just as soon as you develop motor skills or something if you want to get good at it.

00:03:57.880 --> 00:04:09.120
So I always follow that up with all the programming knowledge that I gained between the third grade when I started and probably freshman year of university.

00:04:09.120 --> 00:04:13.840
You could probably learn that in every weekend for a few weeks.

00:04:14.840 --> 00:04:21.520
So it didn't really give me that much of a boost, but it was definitely something I had been interested in for a while.

00:04:21.520 --> 00:04:30.860
So I had started with BASIC, and I found this one book that was really great at teaching me how to program.

00:04:30.860 --> 00:04:36.240
And this was, you know, before Google and before you could easily find a lot of information.

00:04:36.240 --> 00:04:52.180
I didn't even really know that I was specifically looking up books on programming because whenever I went to the library and thought, okay, I'll just find computer books, they would just be sort of abstract and say, like, oh, this is the CPU and this is the printer and this is the keyboard and that sort of thing.

00:04:52.180 --> 00:04:56.000
It wouldn't actually be talking about loops and variables and other things like that.

00:04:56.000 --> 00:04:59.760
But this one book I found, it was great.

00:04:59.760 --> 00:05:02.960
It just gave me the source code for all these small little games.

00:05:02.960 --> 00:05:08.180
And just from that, I was able to copy that code and then make tiny adjustments to it.

00:05:08.180 --> 00:05:17.600
So a few years ago, a friend of mine was the nanny for this precocious 10-year-old who wanted to learn how to program.

00:05:17.600 --> 00:05:23.020
So I tried to find some tutorial on programming like that, but I really couldn't find anything.

00:05:23.020 --> 00:05:29.380
So I just started writing up a short Python tutorial, and that just eventually ballooned into book length.

00:05:29.380 --> 00:05:31.300
Which I just self-published.

00:05:31.300 --> 00:05:33.260
And people seemed to really like it.

00:05:33.260 --> 00:05:35.640
So I wrote a second one and then a third one.

00:05:35.640 --> 00:05:36.600
Now you have a habit.

00:05:36.600 --> 00:05:38.600
Yeah, yeah.

00:05:38.600 --> 00:05:43.160
I kept thinking, like, okay, this will be the last book I write.

00:05:43.160 --> 00:05:46.840
And then, oh, well, I got to come out of retirement to pull off one last heist.

00:05:46.840 --> 00:05:50.020
So that was Automate the Boring Stuff with Python.

00:05:50.020 --> 00:05:51.300
Yeah, that's really cool.

00:05:51.300 --> 00:05:52.860
What was the name of the original book?

00:05:52.860 --> 00:05:57.000
The original book that I found was Invent Your Own Computer Games.

00:05:58.300 --> 00:06:02.020
And back before I realized that this could actually become a huge book.

00:06:02.020 --> 00:06:05.220
So my first book was just Invent Your Own Computer Games with Python.

00:06:05.220 --> 00:06:11.800
And by the time it had blown up a little bit, I already was kind of stuck with that name.

00:06:11.800 --> 00:06:14.440
But it's worked out pretty well.

00:06:14.440 --> 00:06:15.500
Yeah, that's awesome.

00:06:15.500 --> 00:06:20.220
I think it's really inspiring to help young people kind of get started.

00:06:20.220 --> 00:06:22.100
It sounds like that's where your book came from.

00:06:22.700 --> 00:06:29.120
Yeah, it's really great to get emails from people who say, you know, like, I'm 14 years old and I want to learn how to code.

00:06:29.120 --> 00:06:47.360
And I essentially copied the style of that book of just having the complete source code to small programs instead of just only talking about programming concepts abstractly and then leaving it up to the reader to put all those concepts together to actually make something fun.

00:06:47.520 --> 00:07:01.740
Yeah, I think one of the hugest problems learning to program, and it doesn't really matter whether you're a kid or not, is in order to do anything that is at all interesting or seems like you've accomplished something, you have to learn a bunch of little tiny facts.

00:07:01.740 --> 00:07:02.720
Oh, yes.

00:07:02.960 --> 00:07:05.360
Yeah, I've got to learn what a for loop looks like.

00:07:05.360 --> 00:07:07.000
I've got to learn how to clear variables.

00:07:07.000 --> 00:07:08.600
I've got to learn how to import modules.

00:07:08.600 --> 00:07:11.260
And you've got to power through that stuff.

00:07:11.260 --> 00:07:16.400
And somehow, in your mind, you have to say there will be something good on the other side.

00:07:16.400 --> 00:07:21.940
And I think the kind of stuff that you're proposing gets, you know, shortens that gap.

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:24.740
And so fewer people are likely to drop out, I guess.

00:07:24.740 --> 00:07:34.020
Yeah, I mean, I definitely tried to keep all the, in the first book, all the little game programs anywhere between 50 and 200 lines of code.

00:07:34.020 --> 00:07:37.300
I don't think any of the programs are more than 200 lines of code.

00:07:38.560 --> 00:07:42.080
Just because you don't really have to have that much code to make something a lot of fun.

00:07:42.080 --> 00:07:44.300
And Python is actually great about this.

00:07:44.300 --> 00:08:00.220
When I started writing up, like, a hangman program or a tic-tac-toe program, I realized, oh, wow, if I had written this in BASIC or in some other old programming language, this would have been probably about three or four times as long.

00:08:00.220 --> 00:08:07.240
And just that much more that I would have to explain in a book, and I would lose, you know, another standard deviation of readers.

00:08:07.240 --> 00:08:07.920
That's right.

00:08:08.220 --> 00:08:12.120
Here's how you import the header file, and here's how you link the static library.

00:08:12.120 --> 00:08:12.520
Oh, right.

00:08:12.520 --> 00:08:13.760
And it's like, oh, no, we're done.

00:08:13.760 --> 00:08:17.780
And just type out public static void main string args bracket bracket.

00:08:17.780 --> 00:08:19.420
We'll go into why later.

00:08:19.420 --> 00:08:20.100
Yeah.

00:08:20.100 --> 00:08:21.580
Python's great.

00:08:21.580 --> 00:08:23.460
Just, you know, hello world is one line.

00:08:23.460 --> 00:08:24.600
Yeah, Python is great.

00:08:24.600 --> 00:08:30.180
What I really think is cool about it is it's appropriate for this, like, my very first experience in programming.

00:08:30.980 --> 00:08:38.720
And as you probably know, Python is now the most popular language for first year programming courses at universities in the U.S. at least.

00:08:38.720 --> 00:08:39.180
Right?

00:08:39.180 --> 00:08:40.340
Oh, right.

00:08:40.340 --> 00:08:41.000
Yeah, that's awesome.

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:42.040
But it's...

00:08:42.040 --> 00:08:44.240
It's eclipsed Java in that regard.

00:08:44.240 --> 00:08:44.620
Thankfully.

00:08:47.120 --> 00:08:50.660
And it's also appropriate for Instagram.

00:08:50.660 --> 00:08:53.680
And it's appropriate for discuss.

00:08:53.680 --> 00:08:58.100
And, like, these huge scale professional things.

00:08:58.100 --> 00:08:58.360
Right?

00:08:58.360 --> 00:09:03.600
So the fact that it's a spectrum that you don't like, okay, I'm going to learn Scratch until I want to put on my big boy pants.

00:09:03.600 --> 00:09:05.000
And then I've got to go learn Java.

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:05.260
Right?

00:09:05.380 --> 00:09:07.800
It's this continuum that is wonderful, I think.

00:09:07.800 --> 00:09:09.100
Yeah.

00:09:09.100 --> 00:09:17.460
I mean, so Python, as you might know, was just based off of this language ABC, which was developed as a teaching language.

00:09:17.460 --> 00:09:25.720
And it turns out that making a language's syntax just easy and readable is not just good for beginners, but just a good idea in general.

00:09:25.720 --> 00:09:26.240
Right.

00:09:26.240 --> 00:09:30.280
It basically comes down to the realization that code is read way more than it's written.

00:09:30.280 --> 00:09:32.160
Oh, yes, definitely.

