Yeah.

00:09:32.680 --> 00:09:33.860
Definitely.

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:37.820
So let's talk a little bit about your book and some of the topics that kind of surround it.

00:09:37.820 --> 00:09:38.900
Sure.

00:09:38.900 --> 00:09:40.180
Yeah.

00:09:40.180 --> 00:09:49.260
So one of the things that you said is, you know, people feel like, what's your quote, that programming is something like intimidating rocket surgery.

00:09:49.260 --> 00:09:51.080
And it's just scary.

00:09:51.080 --> 00:09:53.680
But probably it shouldn't be.

00:09:53.680 --> 00:09:54.840
What do you think about that?

00:09:54.840 --> 00:10:02.540
It's, yeah, programming definitely has that sort of, you know, you have to be a genius in order to understand this.

00:10:02.620 --> 00:10:07.720
And I suppose a lot of people are less intimidated by computers these days.

00:10:08.720 --> 00:10:09.720
Just because they're more familiar.

00:10:09.720 --> 00:10:10.220
Just because they're more familiar.

00:10:10.220 --> 00:10:24.840
But the idea that I can write software, you know, just like Mark Zuckerberg or Bill Gates can write software and go on to, you know, they, you think that you would have to be a genius in order to program a computer.

00:10:24.840 --> 00:10:29.020
And then that goes on to create a billion dollar company or anything like that.

00:10:29.020 --> 00:10:36.840
Whereas, you know, there's a wide spectrum where, oh, yeah, you could just write little scripts using some, a few programming concepts.

00:10:36.840 --> 00:10:39.780
And these scripts can actually be pretty useful.

00:10:39.780 --> 00:10:46.040
So I started thinking about, well, what kind of things could a typical office worker write?

00:10:46.040 --> 00:10:58.380
I mean, a lot of my non-programming friends would tell me, you know, like today at the office, I spent four hours going through a couple hundred Excel spreadsheets and copying and pasting this one line out of all of them.

00:10:59.560 --> 00:11:04.460
And I would think to myself, like, oh, wow, you could probably have written a script to do that in 20 minutes.

00:11:04.460 --> 00:11:10.620
And it would have taken about two seconds to run and you would have been finished and saved yourself an entire day of work.

00:11:10.620 --> 00:11:10.980
That's right.

00:11:10.980 --> 00:11:13.160
Not just that day, but every day going forward.

00:11:13.160 --> 00:11:14.660
Yeah, exactly.

00:11:14.660 --> 00:11:20.960
In your book, you have a cool story about some college roommates working in retail.

00:11:20.960 --> 00:11:21.960
Can you remember that?

00:11:21.960 --> 00:11:22.420
Can you tell it?

00:11:22.420 --> 00:11:23.580
Oh, yes.

00:11:23.580 --> 00:11:24.380
Yeah.

00:11:24.380 --> 00:11:26.080
So this story is at the very beginning of the book.

00:11:26.520 --> 00:11:29.700
It's one of the things that I remembered when I started writing this.

00:11:29.700 --> 00:11:35.200
This was, I think, my sophomore year college roommate.

00:11:35.200 --> 00:11:39.060
He was telling me about how he was working at this one retail outfit.

00:11:39.060 --> 00:11:47.020
And every once in a while, they would get a huge spreadsheet of product prices of their competitors.

00:11:47.020 --> 00:11:50.800
I didn't ask how they got this spreadsheet.

00:11:51.340 --> 00:11:58.940
But they would have to go through and type in each, you know, product SKU into their database to find their price.

00:11:58.940 --> 00:12:00.420
And then they would have to compare the prices.

00:12:00.420 --> 00:12:06.740
And they'd just mark it out on these massive printouts that they made of hundreds of pages.

00:12:06.740 --> 00:12:15.660
And it would be two or three of them just doing this for two days straight and going through and then just checking to see which prices they should lower in turn.

00:12:15.660 --> 00:12:26.080
And he said, well, you know, if you have the original file that you printed these pages out from, I could probably just write a script to go through and automatically do this.

00:12:26.080 --> 00:12:29.160
And, you know, so it took him like a couple hours.

00:12:29.160 --> 00:12:37.180
And he was just most of that was just consulting documentation and trying to remember how to do various things in C.

00:12:37.540 --> 00:12:39.800
But eventually he just hacked out a tiny script.

00:12:39.800 --> 00:12:49.940
I mean, it was basically look in this spreadsheet, look in this database, and then just see which one's higher and then print out the relevant ones to the screen.

00:12:49.940 --> 00:12:56.040
So, you know, after a few hours of just writing that code and he ran it and it only took a few seconds to run.

00:12:57.260 --> 00:13:02.660
And he basically just sort of saved everybody, you know, multiple people, a couple days of work.

00:13:02.660 --> 00:13:04.060
Yeah, that's fantastic.

00:13:04.060 --> 00:13:05.160
Yeah.

00:13:05.160 --> 00:13:11.920
And so computers are at this point, everybody, you know, is familiar with has access to computers.

00:13:11.920 --> 00:13:13.520
Lots of people have laptops.

00:13:13.520 --> 00:13:15.160
Lots of people have mobile phones.

00:13:16.160 --> 00:13:24.800
But a lot of people don't get the maximum use out of them just because they have to rely on software written by other people.

00:13:24.800 --> 00:13:37.080
So even if you don't want to become a software engineer, though, learning how to program will allow you to make, I don't know, turn it into a much more useful Swiss army knife that can do anything that you need it to.

00:13:37.080 --> 00:13:39.580
There's a lot of people out there like that.

00:13:39.920 --> 00:13:49.300
You know, if you're a lawyer, if you're a doctor and you run a small practice, there are all sorts of things behind the scenes that have nothing to do with lawyers or nothing to do with being doctors.

00:13:49.300 --> 00:13:52.980
But they have to sort of manually go through all this business-y data stuff.

00:13:52.980 --> 00:13:55.540
And that'd be ideal for what you're proposing, right?

00:13:55.540 --> 00:13:57.000
Exactly.

00:13:57.000 --> 00:13:57.400
Yeah.

00:13:57.400 --> 00:14:01.480
It's pretty good when I describe what the programming book is about.

00:14:01.480 --> 00:14:07.880
And it's like, oh, well, it's programming little scripts to automate tasks for people who don't want to really become software engineers.

00:14:07.880 --> 00:14:09.460
They just want to automate things.

00:14:09.460 --> 00:14:13.120
And a lot of people would tell me like, oh, yeah, that actually sounds like a great idea.

00:14:13.120 --> 00:14:17.860
So it was really helpful just sort of nine months into writing this.

00:14:17.860 --> 00:14:23.640
And I have no idea if the world needs yet another programming book or something like that.

00:14:23.640 --> 00:14:42.420
But it's worked out pretty well just because I think a lot of people recognize that large software companies aren't going to write software that does their particular tasks because they have such a specific workflow that's specific to their own practice or their own organization.

00:14:43.900 --> 00:14:47.560
But they would just need a 20-line script to do something.

00:14:47.560 --> 00:14:52.220
And they don't even know what it has to do until suddenly they're faced with this task.

00:14:52.360 --> 00:14:56.980
So just if they had those programming skills themselves, they could work it out themselves.

00:14:56.980 --> 00:14:57.640
Right.

00:14:57.640 --> 00:15:03.040
I mean, otherwise, they're probably paying thousands of dollars and hiring a consulting company.

00:15:03.040 --> 00:15:05.720
Or they're going to somewhere like Elance.

00:15:05.720 --> 00:15:08.180
And they're like, have no idea what they're getting.

00:15:08.180 --> 00:15:11.960
And maybe even more likely they're just not getting it done.

00:15:11.960 --> 00:15:12.380
Right.

00:15:12.520 --> 00:15:13.100
Oh, yeah.

00:15:13.100 --> 00:15:21.600
And once you're going to spending that large amount of money, you sort of want a large application when even that's not necessarily what you really need.

00:15:21.600 --> 00:15:23.040
Yeah, that's right.

